WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.600
I'm a data scientist at Genentech, and today I want to talk to you about the gtsummary package,

00:00:05.600 --> 00:00:08.800
which has like adorably been mentioned in previous two talks, so I love that.

00:00:10.320 --> 00:00:14.800
So this is a bit of a different talk that you might hear about a package at PositConf. Oftentimes

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:20.959
you hear about these new cool tools that you are learning about, and while I think this is a cool

00:00:20.959 --> 00:00:25.840
tool, it's not exactly new. It just turned five years old on Crayon, so like happy birthday gtsummary.

00:00:26.559 --> 00:00:33.439
I want to talk to you a bit today about this journey from honestly being an absolute R noob

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:40.240
to developing a package that was meant really for my team or my department at Sloan Kettering,

00:00:40.240 --> 00:00:44.160
where I was working at the time, and then to maintaining a project that's actually pretty

00:00:44.160 --> 00:00:50.799
widely used in the community now. So picture it, it's New York City, the year is 2018,

00:00:50.799 --> 00:00:55.439
and I'm working as a statistician, a biostatistician at Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center,

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:01.759
and my team and I, we took major pride in the quality of our code and the reproducibility of

00:01:01.759 --> 00:01:06.879
our results, so we're constantly patting ourselves on the back about it. I thought,

00:01:06.879 --> 00:01:11.040
should I share how we were reproducible, because it's a little embarrassing in retrospect,

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:20.720
but what we would do is in Stata, cue the Imperial March music, we would, for example,

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:25.680
if we needed a table one or a demographics table, we would say, hey, well, I need age and grade and

00:01:25.680 --> 00:01:31.360
stage, and I need that in table one format, so it would calculate the median, the IQR,

00:01:31.360 --> 00:01:36.559
what have you, and round them, and it would print it to the console with amber sands between where

00:01:36.559 --> 00:01:40.160
you would see the columns, then we would copy, put it in a Word document, paste,

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:45.040
highlight it, convert it to a table, and we're like, wow, reproducibility.

00:01:45.199 --> 00:01:52.800
So while this was good, you know, we weren't transcribing manually, we weren't retyping

00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:57.040
numbers, it leaves something to be desired, for sure. It was around this time that I

00:01:57.680 --> 00:02:04.160
started hearing some rumblings about something called R Markdown, and it was infinitely superior

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:08.320
to what we were doing, and it was very clear that the team, we needed to make a change.

